            <!-- ==================== SLIDE 11: Challenges ==================== -->
            <div class="slide" id="slide-challenges">
                <div class="content">
                    <h2>Challenge: Maintaining Non-Equilibrium at 1.2 atm</h2>
                    <p>
                        The cold plasma advantage depends on keeping T<sub
                            >e</sub
                        > &gt;&gt; T<sub>g</sub>. Atmospheric pressure fights
                        this.
                    </p>
                    <div
                        style="display:grid; grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr; gap:1.5em; margin:1.5em auto; max-width:850px; text-align:left;"
                    >
                        <div class="collection-card" style="text-align:left;">
                            <div
                                style="font-size:clamp(1.4rem, 2.5vw, 1.8rem); font-weight:700; color:#f59e0b; font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;"
                            >
                                ~10<sup>9</sup> collisions/s
                            </div>
                            <h3 style="color:#c0c0d0;">
                                Energy bleeds into waste heat
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                Every electron-neutral collision transfers
                                kinetic energy into the bulk gas. A large
                                fraction of microwave input heats the gas rather
                                than maintaining high-energy electrons for
                                ionization.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collection-card" style="text-align:left;">
                            <div
                                style="font-size:clamp(1.4rem, 2.5vw, 1.8rem); font-weight:700; color:#ef4444; font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;"
                            >
                                T<sub>g</sub> &rarr; T<sub>e</sub>
                            </div>
                            <h3 style="color:#c0c0d0;">
                                Plasma drifts toward thermal equilibrium
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                As the gas heats beyond 300&deg;C, N<sub>2</sub> begins
                                to dissociate and NO<sub>x</sub> forms &mdash; exactly
                                what the cold plasma was designed to prevent.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div
                        style="display:grid; grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr 1fr; gap:1em; margin:1em auto; max-width:850px;"
                    >
                        <div
                            style="background:rgba(52,211,153,0.05); border:1px solid rgba(52,211,153,0.12); border-radius:8px; padding:0.8em; text-align:center;"
                        >
                            <p class="small" style="color:#34d399;">
                                Limit electron density
                            </p>
                            <p class="small" style="color:#c0c0d0;">
                                0.15&ndash;0.2% ionization fraction
                            </p>
                            <p class="small dim">UAP's approach &#x2713;</p>
                        </div>
                        <div
                            style="background:rgba(52,211,153,0.05); border:1px solid rgba(52,211,153,0.12); border-radius:8px; padding:0.8em; text-align:center;"
                        >
                            <p class="small" style="color:#34d399;">
                                ACM thermal anchor
                            </p>
                            <p class="small" style="color:#c0c0d0;">
                                320 K inlet, 47&ndash;97&deg;C in zone
                            </p>
                            <p class="small dim">UAP's approach &#x2713;</p>
                        </div>
                        <div
                            style="background:rgba(52,211,153,0.05); border:1px solid rgba(52,211,153,0.12); border-radius:8px; padding:0.8em; text-align:center;"
                        >
                            <p class="small" style="color:#34d399;">
                                Multi-port injection
                            </p>
                            <p class="small" style="color:#c0c0d0;">
                                73% coupling at lower total power
                            </p>
                            <p class="small dim">UAP's approach &#x2713;</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <p class="small dim" style="margin-top:0.8em;">
                        The simulation shows a plausible mitigation strategy.
                        The question is whether it scales.
                    </p>
                    <p
                        style="margin-top:1em; padding:0.5em 1em; border-left:3px solid #f59e0b; background:rgba(245,158,11,0.06); border-radius:0 6px 6px 0; display:inline-block;"
                    >
                        <span class="amber" style="font-weight:600;"
                            >Assessment: Plausible mitigation, unproven at
                            scale.</span
                        >
                        <span class="small" style="color:#c0c0d0;">
                            Low ionization fraction + ACM cooling + efficient
                            multi-port injection address the thermalization
                            problem in simulation. Whether ACM cooling scales
                            from 10 kg/hr to commercial throughput is untested.</span
                        >
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ==================== SLIDE: Magnetization Problem ==================== -->
            <div class="slide" id="slide-magnetization">
                <div class="content">
                    <h2>
                        Critical: The <span class="red"
                            >Magnetization Problem</span>
                    </h2>
                    <p style="max-width:800px; margin:0 auto 1.2em;">
                        E&times;B drift requires ions to be <span class="accent"
                            >magnetized</span
                        > &mdash; they must complete a significant cyclotron orbit
                        before their next collision
                    </p>
                    <div
                        style="display:grid; grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr; gap:1.5em; max-width:850px; margin:0 auto; text-align:left;"
                    >
                        <div class="collection-card">
                            <h3 style="color:#ef4444;">The Requirement</h3>
                            <div
                                class="formula"
                                style="color:#ef4444; border-color:rgba(239,68,68,0.15); background:rgba(239,68,68,0.08);"
                            >
                                &omega;<sub>c</sub>&tau; &gt; 1
                            </div>
                            <p>
                                <span class="accent">&omega;<sub>c</sub></span> =
                                cyclotron frequency (how fast an ion orbits in B field)<br
                                />
                                <span class="accent">&tau;</span> = mean time between
                                collisions
                            </p>
                            <p style="margin-top:0.5em;">
                                At 120 kPa, collisions occur at ~<span
                                    class="amber">10<sup>9</sup>/s</span
                                >. The ion must orbit faster than it collides.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collection-card">
                            <h3 style="color:#ef4444;">
                                The Reality at 120 kPa
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                At atmospheric pressure, the gas density is
                                extremely high. The collision frequency
                                overwhelms the cyclotron frequency at
                                <span class="amber">0.05&ndash;0.35 T</span>.
                            </p>
                            <p style="margin-top:0.5em;">
                                Ions travel predominantly along <span
                                    class="amber">electric field lines</span
                                >, negating the magnetic deflection required for
                                species-dependent separation.
                            </p>
                            <p style="margin-top:0.5em;" class="small dim">
                                The spatial divergence in the COMSOL simulation
                                may be an artifact of manually coded
                                mobility-based drag models.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div
                        style="display:grid; grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr; gap:1em; max-width:850px; margin:1em auto;"
                    >
                        <div
                            style="background:rgba(239,68,68,0.05); border:1px solid rgba(239,68,68,0.12); border-radius:8px; padding:0.8em; text-align:center;"
                        >
                            <p class="small" style="color:#ef4444;">
                                Fix: Drop to near-vacuum
                            </p>
                            <p class="small" style="color:#c0c0d0;">
                                Negates the ambient-pressure claim
                            </p>
                            <p class="small dim">
                                Introduces massive compression energy
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div
                            style="background:rgba(239,68,68,0.05); border:1px solid rgba(239,68,68,0.12); border-radius:8px; padding:0.8em; text-align:center;"
                        >
                            <p class="small" style="color:#ef4444;">
                                Fix: Superconducting magnets (tens of T)
                            </p>
                            <p class="small" style="color:#c0c0d0;">
                                Prohibitive capital &amp; cryogenic costs
                            </p>
                            <p class="small dim">
                                Returns to the original patent approach
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <p
                        style="margin-top:1em; padding:0.5em 1em; border-left:3px solid #ef4444; background:rgba(239,68,68,0.06); border-radius:0 6px 6px 0; display:inline-block;"
                    >
                        <span class="red" style="font-weight:600;"
                            >Assessment: Fundamental constraint.</span
                        >
                        <span class="small" style="color:#c0c0d0;">
                            Standard physics solvers could not model this regime
                            directly &mdash; the simulation required custom
                            mobility-based drag models. The observed separation
                            may not represent true E&times;B drift but
                            mobility-driven drag under crossed fields.</span
                        >
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ==================== SLIDE: Parasitic Chemistry ==================== -->
            <div class="slide" id="slide-chemistry">
                <div class="content">
                    <h2>
                        Parasitic Chemistry &amp; <span class="red"
                            >Thermal Artifacts</span>
                    </h2>
                    <p style="max-width:800px; margin:0 auto 1em;">
                        Operating an air plasma at 3&ndash;6 eV electron
                        temperature creates unavoidable side reactions in 78% N<sub
                            >2</sub
                        > / 21% O<sub>2</sub>
                    </p>
                    <div
                        style="display:grid; grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr 1fr; gap:1.2em; max-width:900px; margin:0 auto; text-align:left;"
                    >
                        <div class="collection-card">
                            <h3 style="color:#ef4444;">
                                NO<sub>x</sub> Formation
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                3&ndash;6 eV electrons can break the N<sub
                                    >2</sub
                                > triple bond (9.8 eV dissociation) and O<sub
                                    >2</sub
                                > double bond (5.1 eV). The dominant reaction in atmospheric
                                air plasma is
                                <span class="red">nitrogen oxide</span> formation,
                                not selective ionization of trace gases.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collection-card">
                            <h3 style="color:#ef4444;">
                                Thermal Boundary Artifacts
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                The simulation reports bulk gas at 320&ndash;370
                                K, but this may be an artifact of <span
                                    class="amber"
                                    >forced boundary conditions</span
                                >
                                anchoring the temperature. Absorbing kW into a 10
                                kg/hr stream will likely exceed the 400 K safety interlock.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collection-card">
                            <h3 style="color:#ef4444;">Rapid Recombination</h3>
                            <p>
                                At 120 kPa, ions and electrons recombine on
                                <span class="amber">ns&ndash;&mu;s</span> timescales.
                                This exothermic process continuously dumps heat, requiring
                                constant microwave power to maintain the 0.15&ndash;0.2%
                                ionization fraction.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div
                        style="display:grid; grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr 1fr; gap:0.8em; max-width:900px; margin:1em auto;"
                    >
                        <div
                            style="background:rgba(239,68,68,0.05); border:1px solid rgba(239,68,68,0.12); border-radius:8px; padding:0.8em; text-align:center;"
                        >
                            <p class="small" style="color:#ef4444;">
                                NO<sub>x</sub> mitigation
                            </p>
                            <p class="small" style="color:#c0c0d0;">
                                Requires chemical scrubbing
                            </p>
                            <p class="small dim">Adds cost &amp; complexity</p>
                        </div>
                        <div
                            style="background:rgba(239,68,68,0.05); border:1px solid rgba(239,68,68,0.12); border-radius:8px; padding:0.8em; text-align:center;"
                        >
                            <p class="small" style="color:#ef4444;">
                                Cooling overload
                            </p>
                            <p class="small" style="color:#c0c0d0;">
                                Massive active cooling needed
                            </p>
                            <p class="small dim">
                                Increases parasitic energy load
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div
                            style="background:rgba(239,68,68,0.05); border:1px solid rgba(239,68,68,0.12); border-radius:8px; padding:0.8em; text-align:center;"
                        >
                            <p class="small" style="color:#ef4444;">
                                SEC impact
                            </p>
                            <p class="small" style="color:#c0c0d0;">
                                63 kWh/t target at risk
                            </p>
                            <p class="small dim">
                                All mitigations push energy higher
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <p
                        style="margin-top:1em; padding:0.5em 1em; border-left:3px solid #ef4444; background:rgba(239,68,68,0.06); border-radius:0 6px 6px 0; display:inline-block;"
                    >
                        <span class="red" style="font-weight:600;"
                            >Assessment: Unaddressed in simulation.</span
                        >
                        <span class="small" style="color:#c0c0d0;">
                            The simulation does not model NO<sub>x</sub> formation
                            or the full thermal budget. These parasitic processes
                            would convert the system from a simple electromagnetic
                            separator into a complex chemical processing plant.</span
                        >
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

